		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Ok, I have four 72pin SIMMs. One is a Kingston, one is PNY and the other two are generic vendors. The Kingston module has Toshiba TC514400ASJ-80 RAM, the PNY module has TI TMS44400DJ RAM, and the other two modules have LGS GM71C17403CJ6 RAM. Of the three types, I think that I will use the LGS GM71C17403CJ6 because the datasheet specifies it as 4MB x 4 bit 60ns. Also, what is the best way to remove surface mount chips? I tried using a soldering iron and utility knife, but it just ended up mangling the pins. I tried this technique on some old 30pin SIMMs as to preserve my 72pin SIMMs.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


